05174nam a22005415i 9780822379225DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t19961996ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223792257 a10.1515/97808223792252doi  a(DE-B1597)552850  a(OCoLC)913465472  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aPHI0160002bisacsh1 aBrodsky Lacour, Claudia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLines of Thought :bDiscourse, Architectonics, and the Origin of Modern Philosophy /cClaudia Brodsky Lacour. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1996] 4c©1996  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes on the Text -- tPreface: What Is Modern? -- tPART ONE. DESCARTES' "DESIGN" -- tI Traité or Discours de la méthode -- t2 Autobiographical Discourse: "Fable" as "Tableau" -- t3 The "Discourse" of Thinking: Architectural Design -- t4 The Things a Thinking Thing Thinks -- tPART TWO. THE DISCOURSE OF METHOD -- t5 Letters and Lines: Algebra and Geometry in Descartes' Géométrie -- t6 Writing and Intuition -- tPART THREE. THINKING AS LINE -- t7 The Cogito and Architectural Form -- t8 Staircase as Labyrinth: Eudoxe on Method -- t9 Postscript: Architectural Theory after Descartes -- tEpilogue: The Line between Aesthetics and Knowledge -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is considerably easier to say that modern philosophy began with Descartes than it is to define the modernity and philosophy to which Descartes gave rise. In Lines of Thought, Claudia Brodsky Lacour describes the double origin of modern philosophy in Descartes’s Discours de la méthode and Géométrie, works whose interrelation, she argues, reveals the specific nature of the modern in his thought. Her study examines the roles of discourse and writing in Cartesian method and intuition, and the significance of graphic architectonic form in the genealogy of modern philosophy.While Cartesianism has long served as a synonym for rationalism, the contents of Descartes’s method and cogito have remained infamously resistant to rational analysis. Similarly, although modern phenomenological analyses descend from Descartes’s notion of intuition, the “things” Cartesian intuitions represent bear no resemblance to phenomena. By returning to what Descartes calls the construction of his “foundation” in the Discours, Brodsky Lacour identifies the conceptual problems at the root of Descartes’s literary and aesthetic theory as well as epistemology. If, for Descartes, linear extension and “I” are the only “things” we can know exist, the Cartesian subject of thought, she shows, derives first from the intersection of discourse and drawing, representation and matter. The crux of that intersection, Brodsky Lacour concludes, is and must be the cogito, Descartes’s theoretical extension of thinking into material being. Describable in accordance with the Géométrie as a freely constructed line of thought, the cogito, she argues, extends historically to link philosophy with theories of discursive representation and graphic delineation after Descartes. In conclusion, Brodsky Lacour analyzes such a link in the writings of Claude Perrault, the architectural theorist whose reflections on beauty helped shape the seventeenth-century dispute between “the ancients and the moderns.”Part of a growing body of literary and interdisciplinary considerations of philosophical texts, Lines of Thought will appeal to theorists and historians of literature, architecture, art, and philosophy, and those concerned with the origin and identity of the modern.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aArchitecture and philosophy. 0aMethodology. 0aPhilosophy, Moderny17th century. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z97831107136020 cprintz978082231774640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822379225?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822379225423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822379225/original  a978-3-11-071360-2  Duke University Press Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999c1964d1999  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles